You said: good point... so if my target is
good point... so if my target is VDA only or virtual machine, then network quality should be disable?, 
Copilot said: Excellent observation! Here‚Äôs a nuanced answer based

Excellent observation! Here‚Äôs a nuanced answer based on your scenario:
1. If Your Target is VDA/Virtual Machines Only (No Physical Endpoints)

    Network Quality in UberAgent:
        Purpose: Measures the quality of the network from the endpoint (VDA/VM) to the Citrix infrastructure or other services. Includes metrics like packet loss, latency, and Wi-Fi quality.
        Typical Value: Most valuable when monitoring physical endpoints (laptops, desktops) where the user‚Äôs actual network (Wi-Fi, home/office LAN) might introduce issues.

    In a VDA/VM-only environment:
        Network quality metrics mostly reflect data center network conditions.
        Network path is generally stable, high-speed, and closely monitored by infrastructure tools (Grafana/Telegraf, Azure Monitor, etc.).
        There is less diagnostic value in collecting per-VM ‚Äúnetwork quality‚Äù from UberAgent since you‚Äôre not capturing the true end-user‚Äôs network experience (their device-to-cloud path).

2. Recommendation

    Disable UberAgent‚Äôs Network Quality module if:
        You are only monitoring VDAs/VMs in the data center/cloud.
        You already have infra-level network monitoring via Grafana/Telegraf, Azure Monitor, or Netscaler.

    Enable only if:
        You also want to monitor physical endpoints, or
        You need to diagnose specific in-VM network stack issues (rare, for most VDI cases).

Summary Table
Scenario	UberAgent Network Quality	Rationale
VDA/VM only (no endpoints)	‚ùå Disable	Data center network is well-monitored; user‚Äôs network not visible from VDA
Physical endpoints	‚úîÔ∏è Enable	Captures real user experience from their device to VDI/Cloud

Short Answer:
Yes, if you are only targeting VDAs or virtual machines (no physical endpoints/users), you can safely disable UberAgent‚Äôs Network Quality data collection to reduce Splunk/storage costs‚Äîsince this information overlaps with infra/network monitoring and provides little additional value in a controlled data center network.

